    <!-- Communication Basics Section -->
    <section class="section" id="basics">
        <div class="container">
            <h2 class="section-title">Communication Fundamentals</h2>
            <p class="section-intro">Understanding the basics of communication is essential before diving into specific techniques and strategies.</p>
            
            <div class="stats-container">
                <div class="stat-card">
                    <div class="stat-number">93%</div>
                    <div class="stat-label">Of Communication is Nonverbal</div>
                </div>
                <div class="stat-card">
                    <div class="stat-number">70%</div>
                    <div class="stat-label">Of Business Mistakes Due to Poor Communication</div>
                </div>
                <div class="stat-card">
                    <div class="stat-number">4x</div>
                    <div class="stat-label">More Likely to Be Promoted with Strong Communication</div>
                </div>
                <div class="stat-card">
                    <div class="stat-number">75%</div>
                    <div class="stat-label">Of Employers Value Communication Skills</div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="cards-grid">
                <div class="card">
                    <div class="card-header">
                        <h3><i class="fas fa-exchange-alt"></i> What is Communication?</h3>
                    </div>
                    <div class="card-content">
                        <p>Communication is the process of exchanging information, ideas, thoughts, feelings, and emotions through speech, signals, writing, or behavior.</p>
                        <p>Effective communication involves:</p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Clear transmission of the message</li>
                            <li>Active reception and understanding by the recipient</li>
                            <li>Appropriate feedback or response</li>
                            <li>Minimizing noise or barriers that interfere with the process</li>
                        </ul>
                        <p>Communication is not just about speaking or writing—it's about ensuring your message is received and understood as intended.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="card">
                    <div class="card-header">
                        <h3><i class="fas fa-project-diagram"></i> The Communication Process</h3>
                    </div>
                    <div class="card-content">
                        <p>Understanding the communication process helps identify where breakdowns occur:</p>
                        <ol>
                            <li><strong>Sender:</strong> The person who initiates the communication</li>
                            <li><strong>Message:</strong> The information being communicated</li>
                            <li><strong>Encoding:</strong> Converting thoughts into communicable form</li>
                            <li><strong>Channel:</strong> The medium used to transmit the message</li>
                            <li><strong>Decoding:</strong> Interpreting and making sense of the message</li>
                            <li><strong>Receiver:</strong> The person who receives the message</li>
                            <li><strong>Feedback:</strong> The receiver's response</li>
                            <li><strong>Context:</strong> The situation or environment</li>
                        </ol>
                        <p>Breakdowns can occur at any stage, leading to misunderstandings or miscommunication.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="card">
                    <div class="card-header">
                        <h3><i class="fas fa-layer-group"></i> Types of Communication</h3>
                    </div>
                    <div class="card-content">
                        <p>Communication takes many forms, each with unique characteristics:</p>
                        <ul>
                            <li><strong>Verbal:</strong> Spoken words and language</li>
                            <li><strong>Written:</strong> Text-based communication</li>
                            <li><strong>Nonverbal:</strong> Body language, facial expressions, gestures</li>
                            <li><strong>Visual:</strong> Images, charts, graphs, videos</li>
                            <li><strong>Formal:</strong> Structured, following established rules</li>
                            <li><strong>Informal:</strong> Casual, conversational</li>
                            <li><strong>Internal:</strong> Within an organization</li>
                            <li><strong>External:</strong> With outside stakeholders</li>
                        </ul>
                        <p>Mastering different types of communication allows you to adapt to various situations and audiences.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="tip">
                <h4>The 7 C's of Effective Communication</h4>
                <p>Remember these principles to improve all your communications:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Clear:</strong> Easy to understand, with a single focused message</li>
                    <li><strong>Concise:</strong> Brief, avoiding unnecessary details</li>
                    <li><strong>Concrete:</strong> Specific and supported by facts</li>
                    <li><strong>Correct:</strong> Accurate information and appropriate language</li>
                    <li><strong>Coherent:</strong> Logical flow of ideas</li>
                    <li><strong>Complete:</strong> All necessary information included</li>
                    <li><strong>Courteous:</strong> Respectful, considerate, and empathetic</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
